1010
01:45:56,434 --> 01:45:57,501
That was not answered.

1011
01:45:57,501 --> 01:45:58,767
woman: Right.

1012
01:45:58,767 --> 01:46:00,334
Goldin: That's why you need
further studies.

1013
01:46:00,334 --> 01:46:02,567
Is that only in the adolescents
or is it in younger kids?

1014
01:46:02,567 --> 01:46:04,133
Is it age dependant?

1015
01:46:04,133 --> 01:46:05,601
In fact, another study
that I don't think

1016
01:46:05,601 --> 01:46:08,501
is published yet from our group,
James Gross's lab

1017
01:46:08,501 --> 01:46:10,234
at Stanford Psychophysiology
Laboratory,

1018
01:46:10,234 --> 01:46:13,234
looking at the eight-year olds
up to 22-year olds--

1019
01:46:13,234 --> 01:46:15,501
boys and girls,
every single age--

1020
01:46:15,501 --> 01:46:19,133
the ability to use thinking,
re-interpretation strategies,

1021
01:46:19,133 --> 01:46:22,601
i.e. cognitive regulation or
cognitive reappraisal--

1022
01:46:22,601 --> 01:46:24,534
in clinical, we say
cognitive restructuring--

1023
01:46:24,534 --> 01:46:27,100
to emotional probe,
to emotional reactivity,

1024
01:46:27,100 --> 01:46:29,801
was actually predicted
by cognitive development.

1025
01:46:29,801 --> 01:46:31,133
Which totally makes sense.

1026
01:46:31,133 --> 01:46:35,267
So the older you are,
the more cognitively developed.

1027
01:46:35,267 --> 01:46:37,534
The more cognitive development
you demonstrate

1028
01:46:37,534 --> 01:46:39,767
on neuropsychological tests,
the more you're able

1029
01:46:39,767 --> 01:46:42,400
to use cognitive reappraisal
strategies

1030
01:46:42,400 --> 01:46:44,934
to down regulate
emotional reactivity.

1031
01:46:44,934 --> 01:46:48,334
So there is an age-dependent
thing from at least 8 to 22.

1032
01:46:48,334 --> 01:46:49,601
But then it raises the question,

1033
01:46:49,601 --> 01:46:51,834
"From 22 onwards--70, 80, 90--

1034
01:46:51,834 --> 01:46:53,467
what are we doing?"

1035
01:46:53,467 --> 01:46:55,934
Can we train?
Can we overcome anger?

1036
01:46:55,934 --> 01:46:57,868
Can we overcome low self-esteem?

1037
01:46:57,868 --> 01:47:00,634
Can we overcome insecurity?

1038
01:47:00,634 --> 01:47:02,901
And how?
And what are the best methods?

1039
01:47:02,901 --> 01:47:04,901
Yeah, so I think there's
somebody behind you.

1040
01:47:04,901 --> 01:47:06,567
man: S.I.Y.

1041
01:47:06,567 --> 01:47:08,601
Goldin: S.I.Y.
Search Inside Yourself.

1042
01:47:08,601 --> 01:47:11,067
One method to do that
or at least to begin

1043
01:47:11,067 --> 01:47:12,667
to try to do that.

1044
01:47:12,667 --> 01:47:14,567
man: I'm just wondering
if there's any consensus

1045
01:47:14,567 --> 01:47:17,934
among the critics or skepticism
around this work

1046
01:47:17,934 --> 01:47:19,567
that might be--

1047
01:47:19,567 --> 01:47:23,067
that we might be able
to address as well?

1048
01:47:23,067 --> 01:47:24,734
Goldin: Um, does any--

1049
01:47:24,734 --> 01:47:26,534
I mean,
I have my own skepticism.

1050
01:47:26,534 --> 01:47:27,834
Are you--

1051
01:47:27,834 --> 01:47:28,868
Is there something
in your mind that's come up?

1052
01:47:28,868 --> 01:47:30,200
man: No, no, no, I don't.

1053
01:47:30,200 --> 01:47:32,334
In fact, this is all very new
and very exciting.

1054
01:47:32,334 --> 01:47:33,934
Goldin: Yeah, sure.

1055
01:47:33,934 --> 01:47:35,400
I'm happy to--

1056
01:47:35,400 --> 01:47:36,934
You know, one of the great
things about being in science

1057
01:47:36,934 --> 01:47:40,334
is that we can be skeptical
professionally.

1058
01:47:40,334 --> 01:47:42,901
So I have my skepticism
in the following way.

1059
01:47:42,901 --> 01:47:45,567
I'll try to just briefly--

1060
01:47:45,567 --> 01:47:48,334
So for example,
in cognitive-behavorial therapy,

1061
01:47:48,334 --> 01:47:51,434
which I'm trained in,
it's change oriented.

1062
01:47:51,434 --> 01:47:53,434
Identifying mistakes
in thinking.

1063
01:47:53,434 --> 01:47:55,868
Thinking in ways that
are actually harmful,

1064
01:47:55,868 --> 01:47:59,667
not beneficial, that lead
to feeling worse about myself

1065
01:47:59,667 --> 01:48:01,100
or others.

1066
01:48:01,100 --> 01:48:03,067
One method to work
with that is to identify

1067
01:48:03,067 --> 01:48:06,067
those thoughts, modify them,
change them,

1068
01:48:06,067 --> 01:48:09,667
deconstruct them, find
evidence that those thoughts

1069
01:48:09,667 --> 01:48:13,434
are either not accurate or that
they're not beneficial.

1070
01:48:13,434 --> 01:48:15,868
So that's really a heady,
logical, linguistic,

1071
01:48:15,868 --> 01:48:18,434
language approach.

1072
01:48:18,434 --> 01:48:20,200
Shift.

1073
01:48:20,200 --> 01:48:22,167
I'm also trained in mindfulness
or in meditation.

1074
01:48:22,167 --> 01:48:23,634
Different kinds
of meditation techniques.

1075
01:48:23,634 --> 01:48:25,567
One of which is mindfulness
meditation.

1076
01:48:25,567 --> 01:48:29,968
There, you go for change,
but it's not language based,

1077
01:48:29,968 --> 01:48:33,000
it's not linguistic,
it's not cognitively

1078
01:48:33,000 --> 01:48:34,534
challenging my thoughts.

1079
01:48:34,534 --> 01:48:40,467
It's actually shifting how
I approach my own experience.

1080
01:48:40,467 --> 01:48:44,367
Radically different from the
cognitive-behavioral approach.

1081
01:48:44,367 --> 01:48:48,067
But probably leading
to the same kind

1082
01:48:48,067 --> 01:48:51,501
of psychological flexibility.

1083
01:48:51,501 --> 01:48:53,567
Currently people are--

1084
01:48:53,567 --> 01:48:55,601
How do we know when someone
walks in the door

1085
01:48:55,601 --> 01:48:58,601
or even a friend,
what methods work best for whom?

1086
01:48:58,601 --> 01:49:00,267
We actually don't know that.

1087
01:49:00,267 --> 01:49:03,868
How do know that
a combined approach

1088
01:49:03,868 --> 01:49:07,167
would work best
for Joe or for Sally?

1089
01:49:07,167 --> 01:49:08,834
Currently, we actually
don't know.

1090
01:49:08,834 --> 01:49:10,400
And this is one
of the biggest problems.

1091
01:49:10,400 --> 01:49:12,934
If I train you
in certain skills

1092
01:49:12,934 --> 01:49:14,734
where I assume this
is gonna be helpful for you

1093
01:49:14,734 --> 01:49:16,834
when they're not,
we've just wasted energy,

1094
01:49:16,834 --> 01:49:21,267
time, money, even actually
inducing more frustration.

1095
01:49:21,267 --> 01:49:24,434
So for example, meditation
is not good for everybody.

1096
01:49:24,434 --> 01:49:26,000
We know that as a fact.

1097
01:49:26,000 --> 01:49:28,100
Cognitive-behavioral therapy
doesn't treat

1098
01:49:28,100 --> 01:49:31,167
everyone's anxiety
or depression 100%.

1099
01:49:31,167 --> 01:49:32,834
We know that as well.

1100
01:49:32,834 --> 01:49:35,400
What's in the 30%
that don't get better?

1101
01:49:35,400 --> 01:49:39,033
How can we figure out
who will get better?

1102
01:49:39,033 --> 01:49:40,734
Yeah, yeah, okay.

1103
01:49:40,734 --> 01:49:42,400
I mean, I have many more
questions and doubts

1104
01:49:42,400 --> 01:49:44,968
but that's at least
one of them I can share.

1105
01:49:44,968 --> 01:49:49,467
Yeah.

1106
01:49:49,467 --> 01:49:52,667
woman: You just listed off two
different types of treatment.

1107
01:49:52,667 --> 01:49:55,367
Besides meditation, what are
some other tools that you use?

1108
01:49:55,367 --> 01:49:57,367
I mean, like, can you kinda give
us, like, a case study

1109
01:49:57,367 --> 01:49:58,701
or some examples?

1110
01:49:58,701 --> 01:50:01,267
If I was to walk in your door,
what would we do?

1111
01:50:01,267 --> 01:50:02,567
Goldin: Sure.
How about exercise?

1112
01:50:02,567 --> 01:50:03,934
woman: No.

1113
01:50:03,934 --> 01:50:06,100
Goldin: Exercise
is a powerful mood regulator.

1114
01:50:06,100 --> 01:50:08,634
But one of the things
that happens there--

1115
01:50:08,634 --> 01:50:10,133
'Cause we're actually
doing a study right now.

1116
01:50:10,133 --> 01:50:12,601
Brain imaging pre-post exercise

1117
01:50:12,601 --> 01:50:15,834
for two and a half months
for people with anxiety.

1118
01:50:15,834 --> 01:50:19,334
That may or may not
be just as effective

1119
01:50:19,334 --> 01:50:21,000
as mindfulness meditation

1120
01:50:21,000 --> 01:50:22,400
or even cognitive-behavioral
therapy.

1121
01:50:22,400 --> 01:50:24,901
But it might be
very different mechanisms.

1122
01:50:24,901 --> 01:50:26,133
So that's something.

1123
01:50:26,133 --> 01:50:27,968
A whole other thing
that we're not studying

1124
01:50:27,968 --> 01:50:29,968
that could be very powerful
to study

1125
01:50:29,968 --> 01:50:32,934
since we are so embedded
in logos or language

1126
01:50:32,934 --> 01:50:34,968
is communication skills.

1127
01:50:34,968 --> 01:50:37,300
How we actually
process language.

1128
01:50:37,300 --> 01:50:41,501
Even training ourselves
to use language

1129
01:50:41,501 --> 01:50:44,834
and linguistic processing
in a way that's less harmful

1130
01:50:44,834 --> 01:50:46,834
to self and others.

1131
01:50:46,834 --> 01:50:48,767
That would be
a whole other method

1132
01:50:48,767 --> 01:50:50,067
that's not about therapy.

1133
01:50:50,067 --> 01:50:52,801
It's not about meditation.

1134
01:50:52,801 --> 01:50:55,367
Those are at least two examples
that come to mind.

1135
01:50:55,367 --> 01:50:57,334
And even, like,
we talked about mindfulness.

1136
01:50:57,334 --> 01:50:59,601
Here's a whole other realm
with just compassion.

1137
01:50:59,601 --> 01:51:02,367
So, for example,
here's a thought.

1138
01:51:02,367 --> 01:51:05,100
You take somebody who has an
eating disorder,

1139
01:51:05,100 --> 01:51:10,367
be it bulimia or binging
or whatever or anorexia.

1140
01:51:10,367 --> 01:51:15,267
Could you actually train the
person to view themselves

1141
01:51:15,267 --> 01:51:19,367
via compassion meditation
on the self and others

1142
01:51:19,367 --> 01:51:22,834
to actually move around
the distorted self-view

1143
01:51:22,834 --> 01:51:25,934
that leads
to constriction of food

1144
01:51:25,934 --> 01:51:29,400
or dissolving into food
or vomiting, et cetera?

1145
01:51:29,400 --> 01:51:32,601
I'm not sure that's been studied
but there are approaches.

1146
01:51:32,601 --> 01:51:34,801
So, for example,
I think we have

1147
01:51:34,801 --> 01:51:38,100
to think outside the box
right now.

1148
01:51:38,100 --> 01:51:40,133
Google is a thinking company.

1149
01:51:40,133 --> 01:51:42,567
And that's exactly
what we need to do as well

1150
01:51:42,567 --> 01:51:44,701
instead of just staying
with our normal, you know,

1151
01:51:44,701 --> 01:51:46,234
psychotherapies,
our trainings.

1152
01:51:46,234 --> 01:51:48,267
There may be other ways
to work with the mind

1153
01:51:48,267 --> 01:51:50,968
that could be more powerful
that we just haven't tried yet

1154
01:51:50,968 --> 01:51:52,234
or thought about.

1155
01:51:52,234 --> 01:51:53,968
Just to be clear,
mindfulness meditation

1156
01:51:53,968 --> 01:51:55,367
is one type of meditation.

1157
01:51:55,367 --> 01:51:57,067
There are many, many,
many kinds of meditation,

1158
01:51:57,067 --> 01:51:58,534
for example.

1159
01:51:58,534 --> 01:52:00,000
Many of which haven't even
been translated

1160
01:52:00,000 --> 01:52:02,834
or incorporated
into Western psychotherapy yet.

1161
01:52:02,834 --> 01:52:06,067
Zen has in the dialectic
behavioral therapy,

1162
01:52:06,067 --> 01:52:08,100
mindfulness-based
cognitive therapy, et cetera.

1163
01:52:08,100 --> 01:52:10,000
But there are
many other techniques.

1164
01:52:10,000 --> 01:52:11,868
Yeah.

1165
01:52:11,868 --> 01:52:14,767
That are waiting
to be tried out.

1166
01:52:14,767 --> 01:52:18,334
man: So it's my experience
and I also read

1167
01:52:18,334 --> 01:52:21,367
that basically if you take
any kind of action

1168
01:52:21,367 --> 01:52:24,767
or just express the emotion
then it basically becomes less.

1169
01:52:24,767 --> 01:52:27,133
Has there been any study
on that aspect

1170
01:52:27,133 --> 01:52:29,000
or did you touch that?

1171
01:52:29,000 --> 01:52:30,734
Goldin: Did you say just
expressing the emotion?

1172
01:52:30,734 --> 01:52:33,701
man: Expressing or just any
other kind of action,

1173
01:52:33,701 --> 01:52:37,234
body motion, rather than just
keeping it within?

1174
01:52:37,234 --> 01:52:38,534
Basically, obviously,
it has an effect on you.

1175
01:52:38,534 --> 01:52:40,100
Goldin: Yeah, in general.
Yes.

1176
01:52:40,100 --> 01:52:43,000
Actually there's a very elegant
study by David Creswell.

1177
01:52:43,000 --> 01:52:45,767
He was at UCLA and now he's
at Carnegie Mellon.

1178
01:52:45,767 --> 01:52:48,033
Where he just had people doing
emotional labeling

1179
01:52:48,033 --> 01:52:50,601
using language
in an MRI scanner

1180
01:52:50,601 --> 01:52:54,567
and found that just the act
of applying a word,

1181
01:52:54,567 --> 01:52:57,234
or a label, or a phrase
to describe the emotion

1182
01:52:57,234 --> 01:52:58,968
that one is feeling
in the moment

1183
01:52:58,968 --> 01:53:01,100
helps to reduce
Amagdyla reactivity.

1184
01:53:01,100 --> 01:53:03,734
Helps to actually shift neural
activity in the brain.

1185
01:53:03,734 --> 01:53:05,467
That's emotion labeling.

1186
01:53:05,467 --> 01:53:08,734
Motion expression,
catharsis,

1187
01:53:08,734 --> 01:53:10,567
in many cases can be helpful.

1188
01:53:10,567 --> 01:53:12,567
But we also know
that it has to be done

1189
01:53:12,567 --> 01:53:14,934
in a very skillful manner.

1190
01:53:14,934 --> 01:53:17,300
So, for example,
exposure therapy

1191
01:53:17,300 --> 01:53:20,434
has to do with exposing
one's self to what I fear

1192
01:53:20,434 --> 01:53:23,033
and addressing it.

1193
01:53:23,033 --> 01:53:24,734
So, for example,
exposure therapy

1194
01:53:24,734 --> 01:53:26,901
for post-traumatic
stress disorder

1195
01:53:26,901 --> 01:53:31,033
can either be very effective
if done well, repeatedly,

1196
01:53:31,033 --> 01:53:33,734
in a very concrete fashion,

1197
01:53:33,734 --> 01:53:36,100
but it can also
totally backfire.

1198
01:53:36,100 --> 01:53:40,133
And you can see people actually
melting down emotionally

1199
01:53:40,133 --> 01:53:42,601
when they're trying to express
and relive an emotion.

1200
01:53:42,601 --> 01:53:47,934
So it's more situation and
context and person dependent.

1201
01:53:47,934 --> 01:53:50,367
So no blanket thing
that catharsis

1202
01:53:50,367 --> 01:53:53,234
or emotional expression
is always helpful.

1203
01:53:53,234 --> 01:53:55,901
The other issue here is how is
it affecting the other people?

1204
01:53:55,901 --> 01:53:57,601
Maybe it's beneficial for me.

1205
01:53:57,601 --> 01:53:59,667
But I also--
The people around me--

1206
01:53:59,667 --> 01:54:01,167
If I'm doing it
with a professional

1207
01:54:01,167 --> 01:54:03,701
versus a friend
or at work or whatever,

1208
01:54:03,701 --> 01:54:07,200
I have to recognize that it may
have different repercussions

1209
01:54:07,200 --> 01:54:09,067
depending on
which context I'm in.

1210
01:54:09,067 --> 01:54:11,000
Yeah.

1211
01:54:18,467 --> 01:54:20,467
man: Thank you.
This is wonderful to hear.

1212
01:54:20,467 --> 01:54:23,667
You've mentioned
a lot of great things.

1213
01:54:23,667 --> 01:54:28,868
I'm really curious about
the fact that neuroscience

1214
01:54:28,868 --> 01:54:33,434
is very excited
about compassion recently.

1215
01:54:33,434 --> 01:54:36,868
And it's wonderful when we hear
that sciences are validating

1216
01:54:36,868 --> 01:54:39,234
age-old wisdoms, so.

1217
01:54:39,234 --> 01:54:41,501
The idea of slowing down,
being more mindful,

1218
01:54:41,501 --> 01:54:45,434
being in the present,
good food, exercise, so.

1219
01:54:45,434 --> 01:54:46,434
Goldin: Good friends.

1220
01:54:46,434 --> 01:54:47,734
man: Good friends.

1221
01:54:47,734 --> 01:54:51,400
Good relationships.
All of that good loving, yeah.

1222
01:54:51,400 --> 01:54:54,501
I'm just curious
whether or not you have

1223
01:54:54,501 --> 01:54:57,467
a certain perspective on how
that fits into our society,

1224
01:54:57,467 --> 01:55:01,868
because those age-old wisdoms
are sound and true.

1225
01:55:01,868 --> 01:55:05,634
But in a society where we're
constantly fragmented,

1226
01:55:05,634 --> 01:55:09,133
or even the idea of memory,
it's being fragmented

1227
01:55:09,133 --> 01:55:11,267
even by the fact that we're
searching every day

1228
01:55:11,267 --> 01:55:13,033
and we don't bother
remembering things.

1229
01:55:13,033 --> 01:55:15,801
Memory's important
from an emotional context

1230
01:55:15,801 --> 01:55:18,300
for understanding who we are.

1231
01:55:18,300 --> 01:55:20,868
So, yes, we're understanding it.

1232
01:55:20,868 --> 01:55:22,534
Yes, we're validating it.

1233
01:55:22,534 --> 01:55:25,067
Do you have an opinion
on how we can integrate it

1234
01:55:25,067 --> 01:55:29,300
into our lives
and complimenting, perhaps,

1235
01:55:29,300 --> 01:55:35,234
our need to be fast-paced
and hungry and diverse?

1236
01:55:35,234 --> 01:55:37,234
Goldin: That's a great question.

1237
01:55:37,234 --> 01:55:41,000
And, um...

1238
01:55:41,000 --> 01:55:43,234
Introducing silence
and stillness.

1239
01:55:43,234 --> 01:55:47,167
Appreciation
for silence and stillness.

1240
01:55:47,167 --> 01:55:49,734
Going into stillness
in one's self.

1241
01:55:49,734 --> 01:55:53,067
In little kids.
In families.

1242
01:55:53,067 --> 01:55:57,467
In fact, my favorite studies are
about training whole families

1243
01:55:57,467 --> 01:55:59,934
to become quiet.

1244
01:55:59,934 --> 01:56:04,968
To actually take stillness
as a family exercise.

1245
01:56:04,968 --> 01:56:08,701
Can you imagine taking stillness
as a work exercise?

1246
01:56:08,701 --> 01:56:11,334
So, for example,
our lab meetings.

1247
01:56:11,334 --> 01:56:14,834
My little group,
we begin in silence.

1248
01:56:14,834 --> 01:56:16,501
The Quakers do it.

1249
01:56:16,501 --> 01:56:21,033
Introducing silence
both mentally and communally.

1250
01:56:21,033 --> 01:56:24,000
As a practice,
that's not bizarre or weird.

1251
01:56:24,000 --> 01:56:27,834
That actually reinforces how
people feel about each other.

1252
01:56:27,834 --> 01:56:29,901
But the key thing you're saying
is right.

1253
01:56:29,901 --> 01:56:32,100
How do we integrate this both
intrapersonally--

1254
01:56:32,100 --> 01:56:33,601
Like, in me?

1255
01:56:33,601 --> 01:56:35,467
And that's something that
each person has to figure out.

1256
01:56:35,467 --> 01:56:38,133
How do I find that still,
quiet place inside?

1257
01:56:38,133 --> 01:56:40,200
Nourish it.
Enjoy it.

1258
01:56:40,200 --> 01:56:42,267
Actually, like, enjoy it.

1259
01:56:42,267 --> 01:56:45,133
How do I experience that
with other people?

1260
01:56:45,133 --> 01:56:48,501
So in psychotherapy,
this sensibility

1261
01:56:48,501 --> 01:56:50,067
has kinda been infused lately.

1262
01:56:50,067 --> 01:56:51,968
Mindfulness, acceptance,
et cetera.

1263
01:56:51,968 --> 01:56:54,467
And people are experimenting
both in individual,

1264
01:56:54,467 --> 01:56:55,968
couples, group therapy.

1265
01:56:55,968 --> 01:56:58,901
In workplaces,
people are recognizing

1266
01:56:58,901 --> 01:57:04,067
that well-being
is as monetarily valuable

1267
01:57:04,067 --> 01:57:08,234
to creativity,
to lack of illness,

1268
01:57:08,234 --> 01:57:10,334
to a communal sense,

1269
01:57:10,334 --> 01:57:12,400
and even, for example,
creativity.

1270
01:57:12,400 --> 01:57:14,234
So if the mind--

1271
01:57:14,234 --> 01:57:16,567
If you're a company
that really requires

1272
01:57:16,567 --> 01:57:18,734
thinking outside the box,

1273
01:57:18,734 --> 01:57:20,901
and you know there's different
forms of stress

1274
01:57:20,901 --> 01:57:23,167
that make me box-like--

1275
01:57:23,167 --> 01:57:26,133
Wow, gosh,
I have to address that.

1276
01:57:26,133 --> 01:57:31,234
And actively creating community,
be it on a family level,

1277
01:57:31,234 --> 01:57:33,667
be it amongst people here,
be it even, like,

1278
01:57:33,667 --> 01:57:35,167
a little work team.

1279
01:57:35,167 --> 01:57:37,067
I don't know
what vocabulary you use.

1280
01:57:37,067 --> 01:57:40,634
But introducing that sensibility
either just as a tool

1281
01:57:40,634 --> 01:57:44,167
for people to become
more still, creative, aware.

1282
01:57:44,167 --> 01:57:49,100
Even pausing for a moment
before responding.

1283
01:57:50,734 --> 01:57:52,467
And then again,
it's all of this--

1284
01:57:52,467 --> 01:57:53,801
You know, there's the muscle
of attention

1285
01:57:53,801 --> 01:57:55,367
and anyone can develop that.

1286
01:57:55,367 --> 01:57:56,734
And then there's becoming--

1287
01:57:56,734 --> 01:57:59,901
Search inside yourself
to become more and more aware.

1288
01:57:59,901 --> 01:58:01,734
How does my mind work?

1289
01:58:01,734 --> 01:58:04,133
How does my mind work?
Being curious.

1290
01:58:04,133 --> 01:58:06,634
How do I impact others?

1291
01:58:06,634 --> 01:58:09,434
How do I understand
when I feel off

1292
01:58:09,434 --> 01:58:11,067
or emotionally off-balance?

1293
01:58:11,067 --> 01:58:12,701
How can I bring myself back?

1294
01:58:12,701 --> 01:58:15,067
How can I become more skillful
with myself?

1295
01:58:15,067 --> 01:58:17,100
You know, other people
take care of themselves.

1296
01:58:17,100 --> 01:58:18,467
But just myself.

1297
01:58:18,467 --> 01:58:20,467
So I think it starts
from an individual practice

1298
01:58:20,467 --> 01:58:25,400
and then it will automatically
touch other people.

1299
01:58:25,400 --> 01:58:27,100
So just a simple example,
you know?

1300
01:58:27,100 --> 01:58:29,400
Paul Ekman,
who spoke yesterday on NPR

1301
01:58:29,400 --> 01:58:30,767
and who's, uh--

1302
01:58:30,767 --> 01:58:33,434
He was a pretty intense--

1303
01:58:33,434 --> 01:58:36,200
intense, difficult,
researcher guy.

1304
01:58:36,200 --> 01:58:38,767
He went to India
specifically 'cause

1305
01:58:38,767 --> 01:58:40,934
his daughter wanted
to meet the Dalai Lama.

1306
01:58:40,934 --> 01:58:42,634
I don't think Paul Ekman
was interested.

1307
01:58:42,634 --> 01:58:44,734
He went there
and he was smitten.

1308
01:58:44,734 --> 01:58:46,100
That's the right word.

1309
01:58:46,100 --> 01:58:48,734
Touched, smitten...

1310
01:58:48,734 --> 01:58:51,734
by something inexplicable and so
much so that he said

1311
01:58:51,734 --> 01:58:54,801
yesterday on the radio
that when he saw his wife,

1312
01:58:54,801 --> 01:58:56,868
who did not attend this meeting,

1313
01:58:56,868 --> 01:58:59,467
she said, "You're not
the husband I knew

1314
01:58:59,467 --> 01:59:01,501
for the past several decades."

1315
01:59:01,501 --> 01:59:03,968
He'd been touched by something
and he's still trying

1316
01:59:03,968 --> 01:59:05,501
to figure out what that is.

1317
01:59:05,501 --> 01:59:07,701
So there's also this sense
of contagion.

1318
01:59:07,701 --> 01:59:10,033
So emotional contagion
can either drive us nuts,

1319
01:59:10,033 --> 01:59:13,667
'cause somebody else is,
you know, totally off-balance

1320
01:59:13,667 --> 01:59:14,968
and is making me off-balance.

1321
01:59:14,968 --> 01:59:17,100
That's the negative side
of contagion.

1322
01:59:17,100 --> 01:59:20,334
The other part
can be emotional contagion

1323
01:59:20,334 --> 01:59:22,834
or compassionate contagion
where one person in the room

1324
01:59:22,834 --> 01:59:24,801
is like, present.

1325
01:59:24,801 --> 01:59:27,701
And other people are like,
"Ooh, I feel that."

1326
01:59:27,701 --> 01:59:30,234
That's a positive side
of contagion.

1327
01:59:30,234 --> 01:59:33,367
Being touched by,
influenced by another person's

1328
01:59:33,367 --> 01:59:34,834
inner development.

1329
01:59:34,834 --> 01:59:36,701
So that's possible.

1330
01:59:36,701 --> 01:59:38,567
And we have evidence
that that's possible.

1331
01:59:38,567 --> 01:59:40,167
Yeah.

1332
01:59:40,167 --> 01:59:45,667
Ming: Maybe one last question,
if any.

1333
01:59:45,667 --> 01:59:47,801
woman: Um, maybe this
isn't as related.

1334
01:59:47,801 --> 01:59:51,667
But what's your view
on psychoanalysis and how--

1335
01:59:51,667 --> 01:59:54,534
Is that related at all or--

1336
01:59:54,534 --> 01:59:56,267
I mean, 'cause you
were kind of--

1337
01:59:56,267 --> 01:59:57,667
These are almost--

1338
01:59:57,667 --> 02:00:00,367
Sometimes I wonder
if there are kind of

1339
02:00:00,367 --> 02:00:02,434
bigger things
that would prevent mindfulness

1340
02:00:02,434 --> 02:00:05,868
or cognitive based
therapies from actually

1341
02:00:05,868 --> 02:00:07,901
taking as much effect.

1342
02:00:07,901 --> 02:00:10,567
Goldin: So Mark Epstein,
New York City,

1343
02:00:10,567 --> 02:00:13,234
psychoanalytically trained
psychotherapist,

1344
02:00:13,234 --> 02:00:15,501
also Buddhist practitioner.

1345
02:00:15,501 --> 02:00:17,367
He has several really good books

1346
02:00:17,367 --> 02:00:19,701
addressing exactly
this question.

1347
02:00:19,701 --> 02:00:23,167
Within psychotherapy approaches,
there's a wide range

1348
02:00:23,167 --> 02:00:24,901
of how people work.

1349
02:00:24,901 --> 02:00:26,234
And also it's
different skills

1350
02:00:26,234 --> 02:00:27,968
for different kinds
of problems.

1351
02:00:27,968 --> 02:00:30,334
You would treat elevator phobia
very different

1352
02:00:30,334 --> 02:00:33,534
than relationship phobia,
for example.

1353
02:00:33,534 --> 02:00:35,634
And also, you know,
you go back to Freud.

1354
02:00:35,634 --> 02:00:37,300
He talked about hovering--

1355
02:00:37,300 --> 02:00:38,868
Trying to get
the right vocabulary.

1356
02:00:38,868 --> 02:00:41,167
I think he said
"hovering awareness".

1357
02:00:41,167 --> 02:00:44,434
This ability to just let
the attention just rest

1358
02:00:44,434 --> 02:00:47,667
and hover and be aware.

1359
02:00:47,667 --> 02:00:49,367
And that actually could be--

1360
02:00:49,367 --> 02:00:51,367
That's one aspect of--

1361
02:00:51,367 --> 02:00:53,767
Resting in mindful awareness
with nothing to do,

1362
02:00:53,767 --> 02:00:57,000
nowhere to go,
just observing,

1363
02:00:57,000 --> 02:00:58,300
and enjoying that.

1364
02:00:58,300 --> 02:01:01,067
So, in fact,
that could be something

1365
02:01:01,067 --> 02:01:03,968
that arises
from psychoanalytic practice.

1366
02:01:03,968 --> 02:01:06,067
So not just theory but practice.

1367
02:01:06,067 --> 02:01:08,501
So, yeah, I mean,
we're all humans.

1368
02:01:08,501 --> 02:01:11,033
And we can give
different vocabulary

1369
02:01:11,033 --> 02:01:14,334
but it's the same suffering
with slightly different flavors.

1370
02:01:14,334 --> 02:01:18,801
And it's the same tools
to restore well-being,

1371
02:01:18,801 --> 02:01:20,934
balanced,
psychological flexibility,

1372
02:01:20,934 --> 02:01:22,534
not being stuck.

1373
02:01:22,534 --> 02:01:25,534
And also believing that
I actually can do something.

1374
02:01:25,534 --> 02:01:28,801
That's one of the things that
arises in any form of therapy

1375
02:01:28,801 --> 02:01:30,467
or training
or even friendship--

1376
02:01:30,467 --> 02:01:32,734
True friendship is that,
"Oh, my gosh.

1377
02:01:32,734 --> 02:01:37,334
I can expand.
I can be more than this."

1378
02:01:37,334 --> 02:01:38,968
That is the sense.

1379
02:01:38,968 --> 02:01:40,167
Then you trust that
and you're hopeful

1380
02:01:40,167 --> 02:01:41,534
that something can happen.

1381
02:01:41,534 --> 02:01:42,801
I'm actually doing a study
on hopefulness

1382
02:01:42,801 --> 02:01:43,968
and hopelessness.

1383
02:01:43,968 --> 02:01:45,000
And it really is--

1384
02:01:45,000 --> 02:01:47,400
You can actually see
in the brain.

1385
02:01:47,400 --> 02:01:50,200
You can differentiate
a hopeful state

1386
02:01:50,200 --> 02:01:51,634
or a hopelessness.

1387
02:01:51,634 --> 02:01:54,767
And even about
being able to develop.

1388
02:01:54,767 --> 02:01:57,334
Some people don't believe we can
train the brain.

1389
02:01:57,334 --> 02:01:59,467
And that's
kind of a hopeless state.

1390
02:01:59,467 --> 02:02:02,501
So let's actually
change that with evidence.

1391
02:02:02,501 --> 02:02:04,400
Personal evidence.

1392
02:02:04,400 --> 02:02:05,968
Ming: And with that,
thank you, Philippe.

1393
02:02:05,968 --> 02:02:07,534
Goldin: Okay, thank you.

1394
02:02:07,534 --> 02:02:09,634
[applause]

